Step 3 — Create Storage, Database, and Container Registry

This step prepares the core services your application will use.

3.1 Create S3 Bucket

AWS Console → S3 → Create Bucket

Configuration
Bucket Name:
streamvault-media-<unique-id>

Region:
ap-south-1 (Mumbai)

Block Public Access:
Keep Enabled

Versioning:
Enable

Purpose:

Store uploaded videos
Store logs
Store backups
Store disaster recovery snapshots
3.2 Create RDS MySQL Database

AWS Console → RDS → Create Database

Engine
MySQL
Template
Free Tier
DB Settings
DB Instance Identifier:
streamvault-db

Master Username:
admin

Choose a strong password and save it safely.

Connectivity
VPC:
streamvault-vpc

Subnet Group:
Private Subnets

Public Access:
No

Security Group:
streamvault-rds-sg
Database Configuration
Initial Database Name:
streamvault

Create database.

Wait until status becomes:

Available
3.3 Save RDS Endpoint

After database creation:

RDS → streamvault-db

Copy:

Endpoint
Port

Example:

streamvault-db.xxxxx.ap-south-1.rds.amazonaws.com
3306

You will need this later for Prisma.

3.4 Create ECR Repository

AWS Console → ECR → Create Repository

Create
Repository Name:
streamvault

Visibility:

Private

Create repository.

Purpose:

Stores Docker images
Used by EKS deployments
3.5 Prepare Environment Variables

Inside your project root:

Create:

.env.production

Example:

DATABASE_URL=mysql://admin:PASSWORD@RDS-ENDPOINT:3306/streamvault

AWS_REGION=ap-south-1

S3_BUCKET=streamvault-media-xxxxx

NEXTAUTH_SECRET=your-secret

NODE_ENV=production

Do not commit this file to GitHub.

Add to .gitignore:

.env
.env.production
3.6 Verify Docker Support

From your project root:

docker --version

and

docker compose version

If Docker is not installed:

Install Docker Desktop.

3.7 Create Dockerfile

In project root:

streamvault/
 ├─ Dockerfile

